<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: FILLMORE; ANNIVERSARY TEMBLOR CAUSES NO DAMAGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J.E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Six months to the day after the Northridge earthquake rocked the county, an 
aftershock centered in the San Fernando Valley jolted some Fillmore residents 
but caused no injuries or damage. 
</P>
<P>
 The 3.4-magnitude aftershock of the Jan. 17 earthquake hit at 8:29 a.m. Sunday 
and was centered one mile southeast of Chatsworth, according to a Caltech 
seismologist. 
</P>
<P>
 In Fillmore, Mayor Linda Brewster said she was reading the morning newspaper 
when the temblor hit. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a little eerie, because I was sitting reading about the January quake 
when I felt this jolt," Brewster said. 
</P>
<P>
 A Simi Valley police dispatcher said the small shock was barely discernible 
there. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura County police and sheriff's deputies said there were no reports of 
injury or damage and no calls for service linked to the brief jolt. J.E. 
MITCHELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
