<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRUSH FIRE BREAKS OUT IN SIMI VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J.E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A brush fire broke out in the hills of southwest Simi Valley on Sunday night, 
causing Ventura County Fire Department officials to declare a second alarm and 
to dispatch at least one water-dropping helicopter to the scene. 
</P>
<P>
 The fire broke out around 8:45 p.m. near Trickling Brook Court and as of 10 
p.m. had burned at least 2 acres, according to a fire department spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
 Philip Daley, a resident on Trickling Brook, said the fire at 9:30 p.m. was 
within a half-mile of structures. 
</P>
<P>
 "So far we're just sitting tight," Daley said. "The fire department hasn't 
told us to leave yet. At this point I estimate it's about half-mile away." 
</P>
<P>
 Daley estimated that as many as 10 acres may be consumed by the fire. 
</P>
<P>
 As of 10 p.m. fire department officials began releasing engine companies from 
the scene, but no further information was immediately available. J.E. MITCHELL 
</P>
</TEXT>
