<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: YORBA LINDA; FORMER COUNCILMAN WISNER TO RUN AGAIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Former City Councilman Gene Wisner has announced that he plans to run for City 
Council this November. 
</P>
<P>
 Wisner, who was on the council from 1982-92, did not run for reelection in the 
last general election because he supported a limit of two consecutive terms. 
</P>
<P>
 "Having been out of politics for two years, I have been able to take a hard 
and honest look at both our community and its government," Wisner said in his 
announcement last week. 
</P>
<P>
 Wisner's announcement cited concern for the city's financial position as one 
of several issues on which he is focusing. 
</P>
<P>
 "Because of prudent fiscal management over the last decade, (Yorba Linda) has 
an adequate reserve, but that reserve is slowly being reduced," Wisner said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I will work with the council to strengthen that reserve by closely analyzing 
each and every project and program provided by the city to make sure that every 
dollar spent is of true benefit to the community." 
</P>
<P>
 Wisner has been living at his ranch in San Diego County since April, repairing 
damage to the property caused by last October's fires. 
</P>
<P>
 With the repairs complete, he plans to move back to the city by the end of the 
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071894-0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 061883 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 18, 1994, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 4; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
273 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ANAHEIM; PLANNING PANEL OKS PROPOSAL FOR RINK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A joint proposal by the city and the Walt Disney Co. to build a community ice 
rink in the downtown area glided through the Planning Commission last week. 
</P>
<P>
 The commission voted 6 to 0 to approve the project, which still requires 
approval from the City Council. 
</P>
<P>
 The council may decide upon the proposed ice rink, which would serve both as 
practice site for the Mighty Ducks hockey team and a community youth center, as 
early as next month, city officials say. 
</P>
<P>
 The 100,000-square-foot facility would be built on three acres at the 
southwest corner of Lincoln Avenue and Clementine Street. 
</P>
<P>
 If the project receives council approval in August, the rink may open in 
September, 1995, Disney officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposed facility would house two ice rinks, one Olympic size and the 
other National Hockey League size. The Olympic rink would seat 300 spectators, 
while the NHL rink would hold up to 1,000. 
</P>
<P>
 Disney officials said there would be about 12,800 hours of ice time available 
to the public each year. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks would use the rink only about 200 hours per year, Disney officials 
said at last week's commission hearing. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks now practice at the Glacial Garden Ice Arena in Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposed rink also would be used by Disney's new nonprofit program called 
GOALS -- Growth Opportunities Through Athletics, Learning and Service. 
</P>
<P>
 Modeled after a highly touted New York program named Ice Hockey in Harlem, the 
charitable organization's aim is to teach underprivileged children positive 
values. 
</P>
<P>
 The proposed facility also would include a retail pro shop, meeting rooms, an 
amusement arcade and a restaurant. MARTIN MILLER 
</P>
